<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="76" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,969]" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,727,753]" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named after Dr. T.R. Radhamani (Sirsi, 
<collectingCountry box="[951,1010,727,754]" name="India" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">India</collectingCountry>
) who collected this species during her studies on the diversity of leafhoppers in the Western Ghats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="76" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,969]" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,799,825]" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Viraktamath &amp; Yeshwanth, 2020" authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Yeshwanth" authorityYear="2020" box="[323,504,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Advikus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="radhamaniae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[323,504,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">A. radhamaniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[512,602,799,825]" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[512,602,799,825]" pageId="9" pageNumber="76" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Viraktamath &amp; Yeshwanth, 2020" authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Yeshwanth" authorityYear="2020" box="[658,816,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Advikus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siddappajii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[658,816,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">A. siddappajii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[824,914,799,825]" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[824,914,799,825]" pageId="9" pageNumber="76" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
resemble each other externally but the former can be readily distinguished by the more conically produced crown in front of the eyes and by the presence of dark brown spot ventrad of the pronotal marginal carina, compared to the more roundly produced crown in front of eyes and by the absence of a dark brown spot ventrad of the pronotal lateral marginal carina of the latter. They also have entirely different male genitalia.
</paragraph>
